ac is 1 for mono

ffmpeg -f s16le -ar 48000 -ac 2 -i test_2.pcm test_2.wav
ffplay -f s16le -ar 48000 -ac 2 -i test_2.pcm
 ffmpeg -i short_mixed_stereo_48_no_silence.wav -f s16le -ar 48000 -ac 2 short_mixed_stereo_48_no_silence.pcm
 ffmpeg -i short_mixed_stereo_48_no_silence.wav -f s16le -ar 48000 -ac 1 short_mixed_stereo_48_no_silence.pcm
remove silence 
sox in.wav out4.wav silence 1 0 1% -1 0 1%
detect silence
ffmpeg -i short_mixed_stereo_48_no_silence_1.wav -af silencedetect=noise=-50dB:d=0.01 -f null -



sox rec_out_noslience.wav -r 16000 output.wav
Converts a wav ﬁle to a raw 16-bit signed integer mono ﬁle with 48kHz:
1
 sox conference_rec_48_stereo.wav -b 16  -c 1 -r 16k  conference_rec_16_mono.wa	
sox infile.wav -b 16 -s -c 1 -r 48k -t raw outfile.raw	

ffmpeg - Trim audio file without re-encoding

Use ffmpeg to trim an audio file without re-encoding it.

Trim starting from 10 seconds and end at 16 seconds (total time 6 seconds)

ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -ss 10 -t 6 -acodec copy output.mp3

Trim from 00:02:54.583 to end of file

ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -ss 00:02:54.583 -acodec copy output.mp3

Trim from 00:02:54.583 for 5 minutes (aka 300 seconds)

ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -ss 00:02:54.583 -t 300 -acodec copy output.mp3


